ce:section.ce:para:
It is known that Cys is a kind of amino acid containing thiol, which plays a critical role in biological processes [23]. On account of the high affinity of thiol to Cu2+ [24], the Tb-MC-Cu2+ system is constructed to detect Cys (Fig. 5
                        ). Comparing with the evident quenching of Tb-MCs by Cu2+, when Cys is pre-incubated with Cu2+ followed by the addition of Tb-MCs, the higher fluorescence is obtained. Additionally, the presence of Cys shows inappreciable effect on the fluorescence of Tb-MC aggregates. Therefore, the detection of Cys can be achieved by Tb-MC-Cu2+ system. In order to sensitively detect Cys, the experiment conditions have been optimized. The optimum reaction time between Cu2+ and Cys is 30 min at 25 °C, and the optimum pH range for Cys detection is from 6 to 8 (Figs. S5-S7). Under the optimum conditions, the fluorescence response of the Tb-MC-Cu2+ system gradually enhances with the Cys increasing, and the linear concentration is acquired from 0.02 to 20 μM with LOD 9.67 nM (Fig. 6
                        ). Hence, the strong affinity of Cys toward Cu2+ impedes the fluorescence quenching of Tb-MCs caused by Cu2+, contributing to the emission recovery of Tb-MCs. The principle of detection of Cys based on Tb-MC-Cu2+ system is illustrated in Scheme 2
                        .
